PCOS Survey¶

Context¶

A survey was carried out to know how much is known about PCOS among Nigerian women as well as its latent and potential impacts on the population.

Details on the Dataset:¶

The data contains responses to survey questions. The columns were renamed to make them easier to analyse with code. Here is the list of columns in the engineered dataset:

  • DATE: Datetime- the date and time that the respondent filled the survey, automatically generated by JotForms, the survey service provider.
  • ID: The respondent ID filled in during the data engineering process.
  • AGE: The age group within which the respondent falls, given as intervals 18-24, 25-34,35-44 and 45-54
  • STATE_ORIGIN: The respondent's state of origin. We had respondents respresenting every state in Nigeria including the FCT.
  • STATE_RES : The respondent's state of residence. At least one from overy state in Nigeria and some from outside the country.
  • EDUCATION: The level of education attained by the respondent. VAlues are None, Primary, Secondary and Tertiary
  • HEALTH_INSURANCE: Yes or No responses to whether or not the respondent has health insurance.
  • MONTHLY_INCOME: Income brackets of 0-30,000, 31,000-75,000, 76,000-150,000, 151,000-300,000 and 301,000 and above.
  • EXERCISE : How regularly the respondent exercises. Responses are 4 or more times a week, at least once a week/month/year/None.
  • ALCOHOL : Whether or not the resondent drinks alcohol. Yes/No
  • SMOKING : Whether or not the respondent smokes. Yes/No
  • INSOMNIA : Whether or not the respondent suffers with insomnia. Yes/No
  • MENSES : Whether or the respondent mentruates. Yes/No
  • REGULAR_CYCLE : Whether or not the respondents have a regular menstrual cycle. Yes/No
  • CRAMPS : Whether the respondents suffer cramps and when. Yes/No, yes, during my period, Yes, off my period, Yes, during and off my period.
  • HAVE_KIDS : Whether or not the respondents have children. Yes/No
  • WANT_KIDS : Whether or not the respondent intends to have children. Yes/No
  • DIABETES : Whether the respondent or family member has/had diabetes. Yes/No
  • HBP : Whether the respondent or family has/has high blood pressure. Yes/No
  • PCOS_HI : What, if anything, the respondent knows about PCOS and/or hormonal imbalance. Responses are: I have a fair amount of knowledge/Ihave heard about it but that's all/ Nothing at all/ I have extensive knowledge.
  • TREATMENT : Whether the respondent has ever sought diagnoses/treatment for PCOS. Yes/No
  • TREATMENT_FACILITY : What kind of treatment facility the respondent visited. Conventional(hospital/clinic), Alternative treatment or Both.
  • MEDICINE_PURCHASE : Where the respondent bought medication. Walk-in Pharmacy/online,Nigerian or International?
  • AFFORDABILITY : Rank affordability from 1-5 where 5 is most affordable.
  • SYMPTOMS_1 : First list of symptoms related to PCOS. These include: Fatigue, Acne/Pimples, Mood changes/Depression, Excessive body hair growth, Weight changes and trouble losing weight, Irregular, prolonged, or missed periods, Low sex drive, Hair loss/thinning hair, Pelvic pain, Skin darkening/Hyperpigmentation, Difficulty conceiving, NONE of the above. Respondents could choose any number of symptoms they identify.
  • SYMPTOMS_2 : Second list of symptoms related to PCOS. These are: Anxiety, Mood Swings, Unexplained feeling of sadness, Feelings of hopelessness, Difficulty with concentration, Loss of interest/pleasure in activities, Easily upset/irritable, Excessive crying, NONE of the above Respondents could choose any number of symptoms they identify.
  • S1_GRP : Responses batched by number of symptoms from SYMPTOMS_1.
  • S2_GRP : Responses batched by number of symptoms from SYMPTOMS_2.

# Function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

### Function to plot stacked bar charts for categorical columns
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set()
    ## crosstab
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x, data1["TREATMENT"], margins=True).sort_values(
        by="YES", ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    ## visualising the cross tab
    tab = pd.crosstab(x, data1["TREATMENT"], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by="YES", ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(17, 7))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In [24]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    fig = tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

    return fig
